    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "b29aca218a9e94805849a0d18db557feb63234e1171b381c59913f491dbdf3bf",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s thought this was true but that there are very few such $r$. He could show that the density of $r$ such that at least one such $n$ exist is $0$. \n\nThis problem has been formalised in Lean as part of the Google DeepMind Formal Conjectures project."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "1088cbeb636998bb2646fbbd23f51ebdf9eb4264606835fb5c5ded53fa819334",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Let $p_k$ denote the $k$th prime. For infinitely many $r$ there are at least two integers $p_r<n<p_{r+1}$ all of whose prime factors are $<p_{r+1}-p_r$."
    }
  },
